  "response_text": "# Budget-Friendly Meal Prep on 60 Hours/Week\n\n## Reality check first\n$15/week is tight but doable if you're strategic. You'll need 1-2 hours on one day to prep everything.\n\n## Best bang-for-buck staples\n\n**Proteins** (cheapest per serving):\n- Dried beans/lentils (buy bulk, cook big batches)\n- Eggs (if affordable in your area)\n- Canned fish (watch sales)\n- Chicken leg quarters (often cheaper than breasts)\n\n**Carbs:**\n- Rice, oats, pasta (bulk bins)\n- Potatoes (store for weeks)\n- Bread (day-old sections)\n\n**Vegetables:**\n- Seasonal/on-sale only (carrots, onions, cabbage last longest)\n- Frozen mixed vegetables (often cheaper than fresh, lasts longer)\n- Canned tomatoes\n\n## Realistic prep strategy\n\n- **Sunday:** Cook 2-3 large pots (beans, rice, roasted vegetables)\n- **Mix-and-match containers:** Same base ingredients, different seasonings\n- **Aim for:** 5-7 days of lunches + breakfasts; dinner can be simpler\n\n## Honest limitations\nAt this budget and time commitment, you won't have variety. That's okay—eating the same thing multiple days is fine nutritionally. Focus on:\n- Protein + carb + vegetable per meal\n- Basic salt/oil/spices you already own\n\nWhat's your access like—bulk bins nearby? Do you have freezer space? That changes the strategy.",
